1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,000
Why eye productivity is secretly destroying your career.

2
00:00:04,000 --> 00:00:06,000
My 90-day experiment.

3
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:07,000
Hook.

4
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:09,000
0100-030.

5
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:14,000
I outsourced my entire job to chat GPT for 90 days.

6
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:16,000
My output tripled.

7
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:17,000
My boss loved me.

8
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:20,000
And I almost got fired anyway.

9
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:26,000
Because eye productivity has a dark side that nobody in the tech bro community wants to admit.

10
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Using these tools for everything doesn't just make you dependent.

11
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:34,000
It quietly erases the exact skills that make you hireable,

12
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:38,000
promotable, and creatively dangerous in the first place.

13
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:46,000
And by the end of this story, you'll understand why the smartest people I know are now intentionally using AI less.

14
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:48,000
Not more.

15
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:49,000
Content.

16
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:50,000
Section 1.

17
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:52,000
The GPS Effect.

18
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:54,000
Cognitive Atrophy.

19
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:01,000
She's a marketing manager who decided to automate every cognitive task she possibly could.

20
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:04,000
Chat GPT wrote her emails.

21
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:06,000
It brainstormed her campaigns.

22
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:11,000
It drafted her Slack updates and even generated her performance reviews.

23
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:16,000
For six months, she was the most efficient person in her department.

24
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:19,000
Her manager praised her turnaround time.

25
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:25,000
Then one Monday morning, the company Wi-Fi went down during a critical product launch.

26
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Sarah sat in front of a blank word document for 45 minutes.

27
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:35,000
Unable to write a simple two-page creative brief without an AI crutch.

28
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:37,000
She hadn't lost her job.

29
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:41,000
She had lost her ability to think from first principles.

30
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:44,000
Neuroscientists have a term for this.

31
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:46,000
They call it the GPS Effect.

32
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:53,000
When you use turn-by-turn navigation for every single drive, your hippocampus physically shrinks

33
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:56,000
because your brain stops building cognitive maps.

34
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:01,000
AI is doing the exact same thing to your prefrontal cortex.

35
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:08,000
Every time you outsource your thinking to a chatbot, you're telling your brain that forming ideas independently is optional.

36
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:12,000
An optional muscles atrophy fast the scary part?

37
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:16,000
You don't notice it happening until the Wi-Fi cuts out.

38
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:21,000
Or until your boss asks a strategic question that isn't in the AI's training data.

39
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:25,000
By then, your mental map is already gone.

40
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:31,000
And rebuilding it takes 10 times longer than you expect because you have to relearn how to sit.

41
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:35,000
With uncertainty, Section 2, the competence trap.

42
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:39,000
Then there's Alex, junior developer, Bright Guy,

43
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:44,000
started using GitHub Copilot for practically every line of code.

44
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:48,000
He was shipping tickets three times faster than the senior engineers.

45
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:51,000
Management promoted him within eight months.

46
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:58,000
Then, during a critical site outage at 2 a.m., the AI service was down.

47
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Alex opened the codebase and panicked.

48
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:05,000
He couldn't debug a basic Python loop without autocomplete suggestions.

49
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:11,000
The skills he thought he had were just a reflection of the algorithm holding his hand.

50
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:16,000
Researchers at Stanford ran a controlled study on this exact phenomenon.

51
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:23,000
Programmers who used AI assistance for their daily work scored 40% lower on manual coding.

52
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:25,000
Assessments six months later.

53
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:27,000
But here's the kicker.

54
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:32,000
They rated their own abilities significantly higher than coders who worked alone.

55
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:36,000
It's done in Kruger Fueled by Silicon.

56
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:40,000
Think of it like a pilot who logs 10,000 hours of flight time.

57
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:43,000
But 9,000 of them are on autopilot.

58
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:49,000
When the storm hits and the screens go dark, he doesn't know how to read the instruments.

59
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:54,000
If your entire workflow is AI assisted, you aren't building expertise.

60
00:03:54,000 --> 00:04:00,000
You're curating it, and curated competence shatters the moment the API times out.

61
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:06,000
Or when a client asks you to explain the underlying logic you supposedly wrote.

62
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:08,000
The tool becomes a crutch.

63
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:11,000
And crutches don't make your legs stronger.

64
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:14,000
They just make you forget you ever walked without them.

65
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:17,000
Section 3. The Shadow workload.

66
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:23,000
Mike is a consultant who bragged about his $500 a month AI stack.

67
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:26,000
He had auto transcribing his meetings.

68
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:29,000
Notion AI summarizing his notes.

69
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:31,000
Claude drafting his proposals.

70
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:34,000
And mid-journey generating his slide decks.

71
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:35,000
On paper.

72
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:38,000
He was saving 10 hours a week.

73
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:42,000
In reality, he was spending six hours managing prompts.

74
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:45,000
Fixing AI hallucinations.

75
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:48,000
Copy pasting between platforms.

76
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:54,000
And triple checking research because the model cited three studies that didn't exist economists.

77
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:56,000
Call this the Shadow workload.

78
00:04:56,000 --> 00:05:01,000
Tasks that are created by the very tools designed to eliminate tasks.

79
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:05,000
It's like buying a robot to wash your dishes.

80
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:08,000
But you spend all day repairing the robot.

81
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:10,000
Pre-rinsing its mistakes.

82
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:14,000
And washing the same plate twice because the robot missed a spot.

83
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:18,000
The productivity industry won't show you this math.

84
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:21,000
They sell you the dream of frictionless output.

85
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:26,000
But every AI tool adds a new layer of friction disguised as automation.

86
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:30,000
The real cost isn't the monthly subscription fee.

87
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:35,000
It's the cognitive switching tax of jumping between seven AI assistants.

88
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:40,000
The decision fatigue of choosing which bot to use for which sentence.

89
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:44,000
And the slow erosion of trust in your own deliverables.

90
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:46,000
You don't become more productive.

91
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:52,000
You become an anxious editor of machine guesses instead of an author of human ideas.

92
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:54,000
That identity shift is subtle.

93
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:58,000
But it is absolutely corrosive to long-term mastery.

94
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:01,000
Section 4. The Commodization Cliff.

95
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:06,000
Emma was a copier-writer who used AI to 10X her output.

96
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:09,000
She could knock out 30 blog posts in a day.

97
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:12,000
Her clients loved the speed and the discounted rates.

98
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:17,000
Then her biggest clients send an email that stopped her cold.

99
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:20,000
If you're just prompting AI and light editing the output.

100
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:26,000
Why am I paying you $3,000 a month instead of $20 for the tool myself?

101
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:28,000
Emma had no answer.

102
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:31,000
She had spent a year outsourcing her taste.

103
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:32,000
Her voice.

104
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:35,000
And her strategic thinking to a model.

105
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:39,000
The skills that once made her irreplaceable had become a commodity.

106
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:44,000
There's a rule in economics called the Commodization Trap.

107
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:46,000
When a tool makes a skill scalable.

108
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:50,000
It also makes the human behind it replaceable.

109
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:54,000
Think of it like a chef who only reheats microwave meals.

110
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:58,000
Eventually, the restaurant realizes it doesn't need the chef.

111
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Just the microwave.

112
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:06,000
If your entire value proposition is that you can operate AI faster than your client can.

113
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:08,000
You aren't selling expertise.

114
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:10,000
You're selling access.

115
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:14,000
And access always gets undercut by cheaper technology.

116
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:16,000
Hungry or freelancers.

117
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:17,000
Or eventually.

118
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:22,000
The client's own teenage kid who learns the same prompt you use.

119
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:26,000
The moment your work becomes indistinguishable from pure AI output.

120
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:29,000
You have priced yourself out of relevance.

121
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:31,000
And recovery is brutal.

122
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:34,000
Section 5. The antidote.

123
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:35,000
Strategic friction.

124
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:37,000
So what's the fix?

125
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:43,000
I watched a product lead at a Fintech company implement what he called strategic friction.

126
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:47,000
He. Bandai for first draft thinking entirely.

127
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:48,000
Every morning.

128
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:51,000
He spent 30 minutes with a pen and paper.

129
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:53,000
Mapping out strategy.

130
00:07:53,000 --> 00:07:55,000
Writing outlines.

131
00:07:55,000 --> 00:07:58,000
And wrestling with problems before touching a keyboard.

132
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:04,000
Only after he had formed his own clear thesis did he open chat GPT.

133
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:06,000
And solely to edit.

134
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:07,000
Format.

135
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:09,000
Or stress test his logic.

136
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:11,000
His output dropped by 20%.

137
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:15,000
His originality and accuracy skyrocketed.

138
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:17,000
Six months later.

139
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:23,000
He was the only person on his team who could articulate why their AI driven competitors were making.

140
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:26,000
A catastrophic pricing mistake.

141
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:30,000
He saw the blind spot because he had trained his brain to think.

142
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:32,000
Not just to prompt.

143
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:36,000
Think of AI like a set of weighted plates that an athlete trains with.

144
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:39,000
You don't wear the weights during the game.

145
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:42,000
You wear them during practice so that on game day.

146
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:44,000
Without the weights.

147
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:46,000
You explode past everyone else.

148
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:48,000
AI should be your game day boost.

149
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:51,000
Not your permanent training wheels.

150
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:55,000
The most dangerous thing you can do is forget how to run without them.

151
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:58,000
Use AI to amplify clarity.

152
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:01,000
Not to replace the hard work of forming it.

153
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:02,000
Call to action.

154
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:04,000
Final 30s.

155
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:08,000
Your brain is the only truly irreplaceable asset you own.

156
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:12,000
Before you outsource your next big decision to a chatbot.

157
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:17,000
Ask yourself whether you're building a skill or just renting one for convenience.

158
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:20,000
If you want more contrarian takes on AI.

159
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:22,000
Real productivity.

160
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:27,000
And tools that actually respect your intelligence rather than replacing it.

161
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:30,000
Subscribe and hit the notification bell.

162
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:35,000
I drop one video a week that your AI assistant definitely didn't write.

163
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:37,000
I'll see you in the next one.
